\begin_layout Section
Landau theory of ferroelectric phase transitions
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Landau-phase-transitions"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Phase transitions in ferroelectrics is usually modeled with the Landau phenomeno
logical approach, or Landau–Ginsburg–Devonshire theory.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "dai2020ferroic,bain2017ferroelectrics"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 We can write the free energy 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 of a ferroelectric in the mean-field approach as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F=F_{0}+\frac{\alpha}{2}P+\frac{\beta}{4}P^{2}+\frac{\gamma}{6}P^{6}\cdots-\mathcal{E}P\label{eq:Landau-Free-Energy}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, etc are the Landau parameters, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{0}$
\end_inset

is the free energy density of the disordered (high temperature) phase near
 the transition, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}$
\end_inset

 the external field.
 The strain 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

 is neglected in this discussion, but would add two additional terms to
 the free energy (
\begin_inset Formula $-\frac{1}{2}s_{ik}\sigma_{i}\sigma_{k}+P^{2}Q_{k}\sigma_{k}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{ik}is$
\end_inset

the compliance matrix and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{k}$
\end_inset

 the electrostriction coefficient) which modify the parameters below.
 In the paraelectric phase the Hamiltonian must be invariant under a transformat
ion from 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $-P$
\end_inset

, forcing equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Landau-Free-Energy"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to only contain even powers of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
 The Landau parameters are pressure and temperature dependent, though usually
 only the temperature dependence in 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is considered.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 should switch sign at the transition, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is generally taken as linear in 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 near the transition temperature, taking on the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\alpha_{0}\left(T-T_{0}\right)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "FE-Landau-alpha"

\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the Curie–Weiss transition temperature (
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}\leq T_{C}$
\end_inset

).
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Landau-Free-Energy"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 can be modified to fit thin film ferroelectrics by including the boundary
 conditions
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wong2007simplified"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, but we will keep to the simpler, bulk description and to only three terms
 in the expansion.
 To find the local minimums in the free energy we take the derivative
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial F}{\partial P}=\alpha P+\beta P^{3}+\gamma P^{5}-\mathcal{E}=0\label{eq:Landau-FE-derivative}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}=0$
\end_inset

 to look at the system in the simplest scenario, without external fields,
 giving 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P^{2}=\begin{cases}
0 & Paraelectric\\
\frac{-\beta\pm\sqrt{\beta^{2}-4\alpha\gamma}}{2\gamma} & Ferroelectric
\end{cases}\label{eq:Landau-P^2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 We can then look at two separate cases based on the sign of the second
 term 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

