\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 to remain positive while 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta<0$
\end_inset

 we need the next term 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma>0$
\end_inset

; we will continue to neglect higher order terms as they are increasingly
 small.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is negative, we can drop the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

−
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 term in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Landau-P^2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Above 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}$
\end_inset

 the free energy will have no minimums outside 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{s}=0$
\end_inset

 as the term inside the square root becomes negative.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{s}=\begin{cases}
\pm\sqrt{\frac{-\beta+\sqrt{\beta^{2}-4\alpha_{0}\gamma\left(T-T_{0}\right)}}{2\gamma}} & T<T_{0}\\
0,\,\pm\sqrt{\frac{-\beta+\sqrt{\beta^{2}-4\alpha_{0}\gamma\left(T-T_{0}\right)}}{2\gamma}} & T_{0}<T<T_{1}\\
0 & T>T_{1}
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}$
\end_inset

is the ferroelectric temperature limit.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}<T<T_{C}$
\end_inset

 the two non-zero terms have lower free energy than 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{s}=0$
\end_inset

, while for 
\begin_inset Formula $T>T_{C}$
\end_inset

 the absolute minima occurs at 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{s}=0$
\end_inset

.
 We can find the Curie temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{c}$
\end_inset

 by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(P_{s}=0\right)=F\left(P_{s}=\pm\sqrt{}\right)=0$
\end_inset

 and solving
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T_{C}\approx T_{0}+\frac{3\beta^{2}}{16\alpha_{0}\gamma}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We can do the same for 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(P_{s}\right)=0$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T_{1}=T_{0}+\frac{\beta^{2}}{4\alpha_{0}\gamma}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Allowing us to confirm 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}<T_{C}<T_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "dai2020ferroic,bain2017ferroelectrics"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Landau-First-FvP"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows the free energy as a function of electric fields; as well as 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Landau-Second-PvT"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 the progression of the order parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{s}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is increased from 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{C}$
\end_inset

, to above 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Adding the electric field back in will create an asymmetry in the free
 energy and increase 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 The discontinuity at 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{0}=P_{s}\left(T_{1}\right)=\pm\sqrt{-\frac{3\beta}{4\gamma}}\,.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


